  <HorizontalCard
    title="Altered Emotion Regulation in Children with Early Sensory Challenges"
    img="/SOR_ER.png"
    desc="Adolescence (ages 10–19) is a critical window for developing emotional regulation as children navigate increasingly complex social environments. While emerging research suggests sensory processing difficulties may be linked to mood dysregulation and later anxiety, the relationship between sensory over-responsivity (SOR) and maladaptive emotion regulation strategies remains understudied—particularly regarding directionality and developmental timing. This study investigated the association between SOR and maladaptive emotion regulation in pre-adolescent and middle-adolescent children, examining whether age moderates this relationship. Using a community sample enriched for psychiatric symptoms, we found that over half of at-risk children (50.9%) experience SOR. Critically, age moderated the SOR-emotion regulation link: older adolescents (ages 12–14) with severe SOR were significantly more likely to use avoidance coping strategies compared to peers with mild or no SOR, while no such differences emerged in younger children (ages 8–11). This suggests that SOR may impede the typical developmental shift from maladaptive to adaptive emotion regulation strategies during adolescence—possibly by limiting the social and environmental interactions essential for emotional learning."
    url="#"
  />
