  <HorizontalCard
    title="Developmental Differences in Contextualized Social-emotional Encoding"
    img="/DM_pic.png"
    desc="Social-emotional processing is inherently multimodal—navigating real-world social interactions requires integrating sensory, semantic, and emotional information simultaneously. While decades of research have characterized how the brain processes each of these components individually and how they develop, a critical gap remains: how do these systems work together during naturalistic social cognition, and how does this integration change across development? Traditional experimental paradigms using controlled, decontextualized stimuli struggle to capture this complexity. Movie-watching paradigms offer a promising alternative, providing ecologically valid stimuli that engage multiple processing streams as they would in everyday life. Although prior neuroimaging studies have used naturalistic stimuli to examine sensory, semantic, or emotional processing separately, few have investigated how these components integrate during development. This line of research aims to bridge that gap by examining how the developing brain coordinates these information (n=41 features including emotion, semantic, and lower-level sensory cues) streams during rich, real-world-like social-emotional experiences."
    url="#"
    badge="Ongoing"
  />
  <div class="divider my-0"></div>

  <HorizontalCard
    title="Individual Differences in Emotion Regulation Strategies Shape Neural Discrimination Patterns Among Basic Emotions"
    img="/emodiscrim.png"
    desc="Emotion regulation (ER) strategies, particularly cognitive reappraisal and emotion suppression are constructed from basic cognition and emotion discrimination skills. It plays crucial roles in psychopathologies and socio-emotional functioning, especially across development. While previous research on eye-tracking established that these strategies involve differences in visual-attentional preference of emotions, little is known about how ER strategies relate to the cognitive ability to discriminate between different emotional states. Understanding neural emotion discrimination patterns could provide insights into the neural architecture of ER and explain why individuals differ in their emotional processing capabilities. The goal for this project is to 1) Characterize neural discrimination patterns between basic emotions across development and 2) Investigate how individual differences in emotion regulation strategies relate to these neural discrimination patterns and identify brain regions most strongly predicted regulation strategy. In the preliminary analysis of 361 participants, we found greater use of suppression was significantly associated with reduced neural discrimination between negative emotions (fear, sadness, anger) and excitement in higher-order ventral and dorsal visual pathways. Conversely, enhanced discrimination was observed in lateral somatomotor areas and default mode networks specifically for fear-excitement."
    url="#"
  />
